[[Cricket]] must have reached [[Hertfordshire]] by the end of the 17th century. The earliest reference to cricket in the county is [[1732 English cricket season|dated 1732]] and is also the earliest reference to [[Essex county cricket teams|Essex]] as a county team. On Thursday, 6 July 1732, a team called [[Essex & Hertfordshire cricket team|Essex & Hertfordshire]] played [[London Cricket Club]] in a [[First-class cricket|first-class match]] at [[Epping Forest]] "for £50 a side". The result is unknown.<ref name=GB67>Buckley, ''Fresh Light on 18th Century Cricket'', p. 7.</ref><ref name=ACS20>ACS, ''Important Matches'', p. 20.</ref>

Hertfordshire has not usually been considered a first-class county but its teams did appear frequently throughout the eighteenth century and played in some matches classified as first-class. There was a county organisation of sorts in 1838 and the present [[Hertfordshire County Cricket Club]] was founded on 8 March 1876. It joined the [[Minor Counties Championship]] for the very first season, 1895, and is the only one of the seven competing sides from that season to have maintained membership continuously ever since.<ref>Barclays, p. 490.</ref>

