[[File:PaulmorphyHair.jpg|right|thumb|Paul Morphy]] The '''Morphy number''' is a measure of how closely a [[chess]] player is connected to [[Paul Morphy]] (1837–1884) by way of playing chess games.<ref name="Kingston">[http://www.chesscafe.com/text/skittles258.pdf ''Your Morphy Number is Up'', by Taylor Kingston, PDF]</ref> People who played a chess game with Morphy have a Morphy number of 1. Players who did not play Morphy but played someone with a Morphy number of 1 have a Morphy number of 2. People who played someone with a Morphy number of 2 have a Morphy number of 3, et cetera.
The idea is similar to the [[Erdős number]] for mathematicians and the [[Six Degrees of Kevin Bacon#Bacon numbers|Bacon number]] for actors. For example, [[Viswanathan Anand]], along with many current top players, has a Morphy number of 5: Anand played [[Efim Geller]] (Morphy number 4), who played [[Salo Flohr]] (Morphy number 3), who played [[Géza Maróczy]] (Morphy number 2), who played [[John Owen (chess player)|John Owen]] (Morphy number 1), who played Morphy.<ref name="Kingston" /> Taylor Kingston states that the idea of the Morphy number may have originated in a June 2000 note by [[Tim Krabbé]], who has Morphy number 4.<ref name="Harding" /><ref>[http://www.xs4all.nl/~timkr/chess2/diary_4.htm Tim Krabbé - see item #67]</ref>
[[Image:Morphy Löwenthal 1858.jpg|right|thumb|300Ppx|Morphy and [[Johann Löwenthal|Löwenthal]]]] As of April 2016, [[Leonard Barden]], [[Pal Benko]], [[Arthur Bisguier]], [[Melvin Chernev]], [[Dennis Horne]], [[Borislav Ivkov]], [[Erik Karklins]], [[Franciscus Kuijpers]], [[Aleksandar Matanović]], [[Friðrik Ólafsson]], [[Jonathan Penrose]], [[Oliver Penrose]], and [[Peter Swinnerton-Dyer]] were the only known living players with Morphy number 3.<ref name="Rhine">Frederick Rhine, [http://chicagochess.blogspot.com/2010/09/fun-with-morphy-numbers_21.html Fun with Morphy Numbers]</ref><ref>Barden's comments to [[Tim Harding (chess)|Tim Harding]], [http://www.chesscafe.com/Tim/kibb166.htm ''Playing the Morphy Number Game''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606163132/http://www.chesscafe.com/Tim/kibb166.htm |date=2011-06-06 }}, chesscafe.com, 2010.</ref><ref>[[Edward Winter (chess historian)|Edward Winter]], [http://www.chesshistory.com/winter/winter71.html#6614._Lasker_v_M._Chernev ''Chess Note'' 6614], June 11, 2010. Retrieved on September 15, 2010.</ref>
Many ordinary players have a Morphy number of 6 or less.<ref name=Harding>[http://www.chesscafe.com/text/kibitz166.pdf ''Playing the Morphy Number Game'', by Tim Harding, PDF]</ref>
==Morphy number of famous players== These are players who are important in making links for Morphy numbers.
===Morphy number 1=== Morphy is known to have played about 100 people, but all of the known links for players with Morphy number 2 go through the following five players.<ref name="Kingston" /><ref name="Rhine"/> Some Irish players could go through the Rev. Dr [[George Salmon]], who played in one of Morphy's [[blindfold chess]] simultaneous exhibitions.[http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1227744] {{col-begin|width=75%}} {{col-2}} *[[Adolf Anderssen]] *[[Henry Bird (chess player)|Henry Bird]] *[[James Mortimer (chess player)|James Mortimer]] {{col-2}} *[[John Owen (chess player)|John Owen]] *[[Louis Paulsen]] *[[Paul Morphy#Results|Other opponents]] {{col-end}}
===Morphy number 2=== Everyone in this group played someone in the group above. Some of the most important members of this group follow.<ref name="Kingston" /> Tartakower lost to Mortimer early in his chess career, which spanned beyond WW2, so allowed many younger players to gain a 3.
{{col-begin|width=75%}} {{Col-3}} *[[Semyon Alapin]] *[[Ossip Bernstein]] *[[Joseph Henry Blackburne|Joseph Blackburne]] *[[Amos Burn]] *[[Mikhail Chigorin]] *[[Eugene Ernest Colman]]<ref>Played James Mortimer in the City of London Championship of 1910/11.</ref> *[[Isidor Gunsberg]] *[[David Janowski]] *[[S. Lipschütz]] {{Col-3}} *[[Emanuel Lasker]] *[[George Henry Mackenzie|George Mackenzie]] *[[James Mason (chess player)|James Mason]] *[[Jacques Mieses]] *[[Géza Maróczy]] *[[Reginald Pryce Michell|Reginald Michell]] *[[Harry Nelson Pillsbury|Harry Pillsbury]] *[[Carl Schlechter]] {{Col-3}} *[[Edward Guthlac Sergeant]]<ref>Played James Mortimer in several City of London Championships from 1906 to 1910.</ref> *[[Jackson Showalter]] *[[Wilhelm Steinitz]] *[[Siegbert Tarrasch]] *[[Savielly Tartakower]][http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1455250] *[[Richard Teichmann]] *[[Szymon Winawer]] *[[Eugene Znosko-Borovsky]] *[[Johannes Zukertort]] {{Col-end}}
===Morphy number 3=== Most of the [[chess master|masters]] in this group played several members of the previous group. This group includes some of the most important players for making connections to later generations. Botvinnik and Reshevsky played older masters such as Lasker and Janowski, had long careers, and played many younger players.<ref name="Kingston" /> Najdorf was Tartakower's pupil and they played a number of published games together, and Najdorf played blitz right into his 80s, allowing many younger players to achieve 4. C.J.S. Purdy played Tartakower (2), enabling many Australian players to achieve 4. As of March 2015, fewer than 15 of them are still alive.
{{col-begin|width=75%}} {{Col-3}} *[[James Macrae Aitken]]<ref>JM Aitken beat Savielly Tartakower at Southsea in 1949</ref> *[[Alexander Alekhine]] *[[Conel Hugh O'Donel Alexander]] *[[Leonard Barden]] *[[Pal Benko]] *[[Arthur Bisguier]] *[[Efim Bogolyubov]] *[[Fedor Bogatyrchuk]][http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1100044] *[[Mikhail Botvinnik]] *[[David Bronstein]] *[[José Raúl Capablanca]] *[[Martin Christoffel]] *[[Arnold Denker]] *[[Marcel Duchamp]] *[[Oldřich Duras]] *[[Erich Eliskases]] {{Col-3}}
*[[Max Euwe]] *[[William Fairhurst]] *[[Reuben Fine]] *[[Salo Flohr]] *[[Svetozar Gligorić]] *[[Borislav Ivkov]] *[[Paul Keres]] *[[George Koltanowski]] *[[Čeněk Kottnauer]]<ref>Čeněk Kottnauer played Tartakower at the Staunton Memorial Tournament, Groningen 1946.</ref> *[[Franciscus Kuijpers]]<ref name="ReferenceA">Played Ossip Bernstein at the 1961 IBM Amsterdam tournament.</ref> *[[Kick Langeweg]]<ref name="ReferenceA"/> *[[Bent Larsen]]<ref name="Rhine" /> *[[Edward Lasker]] *[[Andor Lilienthal]] *[[Aleksandar Matanović]] *[[Frank Marshall (chess player)|Frank Marshall]] *[[Stuart Milner-Barry]] {{Col-3}} *[[Miguel Najdorf]][http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chess.pl?pid=10247&pid2=21930] *[[Aron Nimzowitsch]] *[[Friðrik Ólafsson]] *[[Jonathan Penrose]] *[[Arturo Pomar]] *[[Lodewijk Prins]] *[[C.J.S. Purdy]][http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1270333] *[[Samuel Reshevsky]] *[[Akiba Rubinstein]] *[[Friedrich Sämisch]] *[[Rudolf Spielmann]] *[[Herman Steiner]] *[[Milan Vidmar]] *[[Robert Wade (chess player)|Robert Wade]]<ref>Robert Wade played Savielly Tartakower twice, in 1951 (Staunton Memorial) and 1953 (Hastings). He also defeated Ossip Bernstein at the IBM Amsterdam tournament in 1961.</ref> *[[Norman T. Whitaker|Norman Whitaker]] *[[Baruch Harold Wood]]<ref>Played Eugene Znosko-Borovsky at Baam in 1947.</ref> {{Col-end}}
===Morphy number 4=== {{As of|2013}} many of these players are still alive; a few (such as Short) are still active.<ref name="Kingston" />
{{col-begin|width=75%}} {{Col-3}} *[[Ulf Andersson]] *[[Keith Arkell]] *[[Yuri Averbakh]] *[[Alexander Beliavsky]] *[[Isaac Boleslavsky]] *[[Donald Byrne]] *[[Mark Dvoretsky]] *[[Ben Finegold]][http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1000275] *[[Bobby Fischer]] *[[Semyon Furman]] *[[Efim Geller]] *[[Vlastimil Hort]] *[[Robert Hübner]] {{Col-3}}
*[[Anatoly Karpov]] *[[Garry Kasparov]] *[[Ratmir Kholmov]] *[[Viktor Korchnoi]] *[[Alexander Kotov]] *[[Gary Lane]] *[[Ljubomir Ljubojević]] *[[Tony Miles]] *[[John Nunn]] *[[Bruce Pandolfini]] *[[Tigran Petrosian]] *[[Susan Polgar]] *[[Lev Polugaevsky]]
{{Col-3}} *[[Lajos Portisch]] *[[Hans Ree]] *[[Ortvin Sarapu]][http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1269019] *[[Yasser Seirawan]] *[[Nigel Short]] *[[Vasily Smyslov]] *[[Boris Spassky]] *[[László Szabó (chess player)|László Szabó]] *[[Mark Taimanov]] *[[Mikhail Tal]] *[[Jan Timman]] *[[Rafael Vaganian]] *[[Walter Browne]] {{Col-end}}
